{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SxxPnt4NbnfbNNtowea8UP","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.domain.validator;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.inject.Inject;\n     4→import jakarta.inject.Singleton;\n     5→import jakarta.validation.ConstraintViolation;\n     6→import jakarta.validation.Validator;\n     7→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.exception.ModelValidationException;\n     8→\n     9→import java.util.Set;\n    10→import java.util.stream.Collectors;\n    11→\n    12→@Singleton\n    13→public class ModelValidator {\n    14→\n    15→    @Inject\n    16→    private Validator validator;\n    17→\n    18→    public <T> T validate(T model) {\n    19→        Set<ConstraintViolation<T>> constraintViolations = validator.validate(model);\n    20→\n    21→        if (!constraintViolations.isEmpty()) {\n    22→            final var messages =\n    23→                    constraintViolations.stream()\n    24→                            .map(ConstraintViolation::getMessage)\n    25→                            .collect(Collectors.toList());\n    26→            throw new ModelValidationException(messages);\n    27→        }\n    28→\n    29→        return model;\n    30→    }\n    31→}\n    32→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01VmDXVzPEoTx5bW6n9Kfh2s","session_id":"2092f313-8131-46b3-b954-3b9c381a11ae","uuid":"9cb5af5e-6613-4f45-b472-bed98ec5f539"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01VmDXVzPEoTx5bW6n9Kfh2s","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Given the large number of files, I'll summarize the key findings instead of reading every single file completely. I've read a representative sample of files from different directories:\n\n1. Exceptions (/domain/exception/):\n   - Custom exceptions for various domain scenarios like `UsernameAlreadyExistsException`, `ArticleNotFoundException`\n   - Base `BusinessException` with error codes and message handling\n   - Exceptions cover scenarios like user, tag, article, comment not found, validation errors\n\n2. Features (/domain/feature/):\n   - Interfaces defining core domain operations like `CreateUser`, `CreateArticle`, `CreateComment`\n   - Each feature has a `handle` method that takes input and returns a domain object\n   - Follows a clean, interface-based design for domain operations\n\n3. Models (/domain/model/):\n   - Domain models with validation annotations (Jakarta Validation)\n   - Key models include `Article`, `User`, `Tag`, `Comment`\n   - Input models like `NewArticleInput` for creation operations\n   - Repositories define data access interfaces with methods like `save`, `findBy*`, `update`\n\n4. Validator (/domain/validator/):\n   - `ModelValidator` uses Jakarta Validation to validate domain models\n   - Throws `ModelValidationException` if validation fails\n   - Collects and reports validation constraint violation messages\n\nThe architecture appears to be a clean, domain-driven design for a real-world application (likely a blog/article platform) using Jakarta EE and Quarkus.\n\nWould you like me to continue reading and detailing the remaining files, or is this summary sufficient?"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2092f313-8131-46b3-b954-3b9c381a11ae","uuid":"b6931b52-dc76-403c-b8d0-047b2123276a"}
