{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01HwAewp4TEYaHtQdKyxPG5P","type":"tool_result","content":"*   Trying ::1:33762...\n* Connected to localhost (::1) port 33762 (#0)\n> POST /api/users HTTP/1.1\r\n> Host: localhost:33762\r\n> User-Agent: curl/7.76.1\r\n> Accept: */*\r\n> Content-Type: application/json\r\n> Content-Length: 86\r\n> \r\n} [86 bytes data]\n* Mark bundle as not supporting multiuse\n< HTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request\r\n< content-length: 0\r\n< \r\n* Connection #0 to host localhost left intact","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2092f313-8131-46b3-b954-3b9c381a11ae","uuid":"c611734f-0cd7-4a5c-82e6-93929f85df3b"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01VZ5Jvvty1WQFVjJzJCayue","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"400 with empty body. This suggests a deserialization issue. The request body uses `@JsonRootName(\"user\")` pattern and `WRAP_ROOT_VALUE` / `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE`. In Quarkus with `quarkus-rest-jackson`, the default ObjectMapper doesn't have these features enabled. The resource classes use wrapper request classes (like `NewUserRequestWrapper`) which handle the wrapping.\n\nLet me check the UsersResource to understand the exact endpoint:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":310,"cache_read_input_tokens":135038,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":310,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":235},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2092f313-8131-46b3-b954-3b9c381a11ae","uuid":"52162f35-09af-4a01-bd2c-56040a37596d"}
